Machine Learning for Graphs, and more

Software assets relation to this demo

Welcome to Property Graph feature of Oracle Database.

The Property Graph feature of Oracle Database offers powerful graph support for Oracle database, to explore and discover complex relationships in data sets such as customer data, social networks, and financial transactions, for applications in product recommendation, fraud detection, risk analysis, targeted marketing, and more.

This high performance Graph feature delivers advanced graph query language support, developer APIs, and analytics capabilities with nearly 60 pre-built algorithms.

The Property Graph features including the PGQL (Property Graph Query Language) support is available from Oracle Database 12.2 onward. Starting from Oracle Database Release 23c Free - Developer Release, you can also create and query property graphs using SQL, as defined in the SQL:2023 standard.

Oracle Graph Server and Client is a software package that works with the Property Graph feature in Oracle Database. It includes graph tools, client libraries, and Oracle Graph Server for running graph analytics algorithms. Oracle Graph Server and Client releases four times a year and its release version number is not related to the Oracle Database Release version number.

Graph Studio is an integrated, self-service tool to work with graphs. It includes:

  • Automated graph modeling
  • Extensive graph analytics and graph query support
  • Advanced notebooks and integrated visualization
  • Automated install, upgrade, and provisioning

Graph Studio is included in Autonomous Database Free Tier, Autonomous Data Warehouse on Shared Infrastructure, and Autonomous Transaction Processing on Shared Infrastructure. It is not a part of APEX Service or Autonomous JSON.

Define the graph

Build the graph on top of the existing tables without replicating the original data.

%pgql-rdbms
/* Create the graph */
CREATE PROPERTY GRAPH cora_graph
    VERTEX TABLES (  
        CORA_CONTENT  
            KEY ( "PAPER_ID" )  
            LABEL "PAPER"   
            PROPERTIES ARE ALL COLUMNS  
    )  
    EDGE TABLES (  
        CORA_CITES  
            KEY ( "ID" )  
            SOURCE KEY ( "CITING" ) REFERENCES "CORA_CONTENT"( "PAPER_ID" )  
            DESTINATION KEY ( "CITED" ) REFERENCES "CORA_CONTENT"( "PAPER_ID" )  
            LABEL "CITE"  
            PROPERTIES ARE ALL COLUMNS  
    )  
OPTIONS (PG_VIEW)   
 
  • Text
Graph successfully created
%pgql-rdbms
/* Drop the graph */
DROP PROPERTY GRAPH cora_graph
 
  • Text
Graph successfully dropped

Load/unload the graph

Load the graph into memory by retrieving the data from the database and building in-memory data structures optimized for graph analytics.

 
  • HTML
  • Text

Get to know your graph

%java-pgx
// Load the graph using the Java API
var GRAPH_NAME="CORA_GRAPH";
// Try getting the graph from the in-memory graph server
PgxGraph graph = session.getGraph(GRAPH_NAME);
// If it does not exist read it into memory
if (graph == null) {
    session.readGraphByName(
        GRAPH_NAME, 
        GraphSource.PG_VIEW, 
        ReadGraphOption.optimizeFor(GraphOptimizedFor.READ),
        ReadGraphOption.onMissingVertex(OnMissingVertex.IGNORE_EDGE));
    out.println ("Graph "+ GRAPH_NAME + " successfully loaded");
    graph = session.getGraph(GRAPH_NAME);
} else {
   // out.println ("Graph "+ GRAPH_NAME + " already loaded");
   out.println ("Graph '"+ graph.getName() + "' already loaded");
}
out.println ("# of Vertices: "+graph.getNumVertices());
out.println ("# of Edges: "+graph.getNumEdges());

%python-pgx

    graph.destroy()
    print('The graph ' + graph_name + ' has been destroyed.')
else:
    print('The graph ' + graph_name +' does not exist.')

out.println("Graph Name\tMemory (MB)\tIs Transient\tCreated\t# Vertices\t# Edges\t# Snapshots");
for (PgxGraph g : session.getGraphs().values()) {
  out.printf(
    "%s\t%s\t%s\t%s\t%s\t%s\n", 
    g.getName(),
    g.getMemoryMb(),
    g.isTransient(),
    g.getCreationTimestamp(),
    g.getNumVertices(),
    g.getNumEdges(),
    session.getAvailableSnapshots(g).size()
  );
}

    print ("\nEdge properties:")
    for v in g.get_edge_properties():
        print ("    ", v.name, "type:", v.type)            
    print ("\nVertex properties:")
    for v in g.get_vertex_properties():
        print ("    ", v.name, "type:", v.type)
    # g.close()

Use PGQL to query the graph

PGQL - Property Graph Query Language; a SQL-like language for graph pattern-matching.

%pgql-pgx
/* Show types of vertices according to their label */
SELECT label(a), count(a) as cnt 
FROM MATCH (a) ON cora_graph
GROUP BY label(a)
ORDER BY label(a)

/* Fixed path length pattern-matching query: Find papers citing paper with ID 31336 and papers that are cited by paper with ID 31336 */
SELECT a,c,b
FROM MATCH (a) -[c IS CITE]- (b IS PAPER) ON cora_graph
WHERE a.paper_id = 31336

Use Graph Algorithms to analyze the graph

%python-pgx
# Load the graph into memory if not yet loaded
GRAPH_NAME="CORA_GRAPH"
graph = session.get_graph(GRAPH_NAME);
if (graph == None) :
    session.read_graph_by_name(GRAPH_NAME, "pg_view")
    print("Graph "+ GRAPH_NAME + " successfully loaded")
    graph = session.get_graph(GRAPH_NAME)
else :
    print("Graph '"+ GRAPH_NAME + "' already loaded")

Algorithm: Count Triangles

Triangle counting gives an overview of the amount of connections between vertices in neighborhoods.

%python-pgx
# Count triangles in the graph
analyst.count_triangles(graph, sort_vertices_by_degree=True);

Algorithm: PageRank

A high PageRank value is a measure for the importants of a paper.

%python-pgx
# Destroy existing properties generated by running the PageRank algorithm before
graph.destroy_vertex_property_if_exists("pagerank")
# Call the algorithm
analyst.pagerank(graph, 0.001, 0.85, 100)
 
  • Text
VertexProperty(name: pagerank, type: double, graph: CORA_GRAPH)
%pgql-pgx
/* List papers in descending order of PageRank values */
SELECT a.paper_id as paper, a.label, a.pagerank AS pageRank, IN_DEGREE(a) AS in_degree, OUT_DEGREE(a) AS out_degree
FROM MATCH (a) ON cora_graph
ORDER BY pageRank DESC
LIMIT 50

Algorithm: Betweenness Centrality

Betweenness centrality is a way of detecting the amount of influence a node has over the flow of information in a graph. It is often used to find nodes that serve as a bridge from one part of a graph to another.

%python-pgx
# Destroy the edge property if it already exists
graph.destroy_edge_property_if_exists("betweenness")
# Call the algorithm
analyst.vertex_betweenness_centrality(graph, bc="betweenness")
 
  • Text
VertexProperty(name: betweenness, type: double, graph: CORA_GRAPH)
%pgql-pgx
/* Show the top 10 papers for betweenness centrality */
SELECT a.paper_id AS paper, a.betweenness
FROM MATCH (a) ON cora_graph 
ORDER BY a.betweenness DESC
LIMIT 10

Algorithm: Supervised GraphWise

Supervised GraphWise is an inductive vertex representation learning algorithm which is able to leverage vertex feature information. It can be applied to a wide variety of tasks, including vertex classification and link prediction.

A Supervised GraphWise model consists of two graph convolutional layers followed by several prediction layers.
The forward pass through a convolutional layer for a vertex proceeds as follows:

  • A set of neighbors of the vertex is sampled.
  • The previous layer representations of the neighbors are mean-aggregated, and the aggregated features are concatenated with the previous layer representation of the vertex.
  • This concatenated vector is multiplied with weights, and a bias vector is added.
  • The result is normalized to such that the layer output has unit norm.

The prediction layers are standard neural network layers.

%python-pgx
# Load the graph into memory
GRAPH_NAME="CORA_GRAPH"
graph = session.get_graph(GRAPH_NAME);
if (graph == None) :
    session.read_graph_by_name(GRAPH_NAME, "pg_view")
    print("Graph "+ GRAPH_NAME + " successfully loaded")
    graph = session.get_graph(GRAPH_NAME)
else :
    print("Graph '"+ GRAPH_NAME + "' already loaded")

Step 2: Split the graph into a train and a test graph

%python-pgx
# Import  VertexFilter
from pypgx.api.filters import VertexFilter
%python-pgx
# Set a vertex filter to create the train graph
vertex_filter = VertexFilter.from_pgql_result_set(
    session.query_pgql("SELECT v FROM MATCH (v) ON cora_graph WHERE v.paper_id % 4 > 0"), 
    "v"
)
train_graph = graph.filter(vertex_filter, name="CORA_TRAIN_SUBSET_GRAPH")

%sql
/* Show papers where the predicted label differs from the original label */
SELECT
    l2.paper_id,
    l2.label AS label,
    l1.label AS predicted_label
FROM 
    (
        SELECT
            REGEXP_SUBSTR("vertexId", '(.+)', 1, 1, NULL,1) AS vertexid,
            "label" AS label
        FROM
            cora_labels
    ) l1
JOIN 
    (
        SELECT
            paper_id,
            label
        FROM
            cora_content
    ) l2 
ON l1.vertexid = l2.paper_id
WHERE l1.label <> l2.label
ORDER BY l2.paper_id

Clean up

%python-pgx
# Destroy the model

%python-pgx
# Unload the graph if it is loaded into memory
graph_name = "CORA_GRAPH"
graph = session.get_graph(graph_name)
if type(graph) == pypgx.api._pgx_graph.PgxGraph:
    graph.destroy()
    print('The graph ' + graph_name + ' has been destroyed.')
else:
    print('The graph ' + graph_name +' does not exist.')
